<h1>Assessments</h1>

<p>Assessments are ways to measure to what extent students are achieving the Student Learning
Outcomes.</p>

<p>The faculty were surveyed and asked to map the outcomes to their respective undergraduate
classes. They were then asked which assessments would be used to measure those outcomes. For your
subject, you will see each assessment listed. Each assessment will be used to measure how many
students meet the outcomes selected by the faculty.</p>

<hr>

<h2>Basic Information</h2>

<h4>Types of Assessments</h4>

<p>There are two types of assessments:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Direct:</strong> grades from exams, problem sets, projects</li>
  <li>
    <strong>Indirect:</strong> survey results, participation in a special program (e.g. UPOP or
    UROP)
  </li>
</ul>

<h4>Example Direct Assessment</h4>

<p>Below is an example assessment for the subject EECS 2013 self-study. This assessment would be
used to measure the ABET standard outcome: a &mdash; an ability to apply knowledge of mathematics,
science, and engineering.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Subject:</strong> EECS 2013 self-study</li>
  <li><strong>Assignment Name &amp; Description:</strong> 6.02 Quiz 1, Bits module</li>
  <li><strong>Minimum Grade:</strong> Students score 85 or higher</li>
  <li><strong>Target Percentage:</strong> 80% of students should achieve the minimum grade</li>
</ul>

